<p>This tooth's distal root is experiencing a fraction that has created bone loss at the furcation and below. This can be said with confidence as the distal root has unusual radiolucency near the cementoenamel junction, and the radiolucency at the furcation site has a J shape. This happens either due to bruxism, a failed RCT, a retreatment of an RCT that was already brittle, or just age. The suggested tx plan is EXT with bone removal, bone grafting, and implant-supported crown. If unable, I still would suggest replacing this tooth in general as #30 is a first molar, and I would like to avoid the mesial drift of #31. It already has a large filling, and its shifting would put it at a higher risk of an accelerated progression further down the tooth death spiral. </p>
